  "text": "As discussed in Section III-D, if T (x, u) were known, we could use DIRCOL to synthesize a trajectory that optimally solves our task, and a policy π : X → U that tracks this trajectory using TVLQR. If T (x, u) is not known, it can be learned from data observed while interacting with the environment. Figure 2 shows the architecture for model-based reinforcement learning used in this work. Polydoros et al.provide a survey of a variety of other approaches [CITATION_1] . Initially, an episode of training data is generated by randomly actuating the system and observing its state-transitions. A model, T (x, u) is learned from the dataset. The model is then passed through DIRCOL and TVLQR to generate a policy π(x) that, if the model were accurate, would solve the task. Naturally, the model being imperfect, this would not solve the task, but visit novel states.",
